                     <interp inst="t18270531-332-defend1781" type="age" value="28"></interp>
                  </persName>
             was indicted for <rs id="t18270531-332-off1784" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18270531-332-off1784" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270531-332-off1784" type="offenceSubcategory" value="pocketpicking"></interp>
               stealing, on the <rs id="t18270531-332-cd1785" type="crimeDate">19th of May</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270531-332-off1784 t18270531-332-cd1785"></join>, 1 handkerchief, value 5s., the goods of 
                     <persName id="t18270531-332-victim1782" type="victimName">
                        Richard Hodgson 
                        Galloway
                     <interp inst="t18270531-332-victim1782" type="surname" value="Galloway"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18270531-332-victim1782" type="given" value="Richard Hodgson"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18270531-332-victim1782" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270531-332-off1784 t18270531-332-victim1782"></join>
                     </persName>
                  , from his person
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>RICHARD HODGSON GALLOWAY. I am an <rs id="t18270531-332-viclabel1786" type="occupation">engineer</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270531-332-victim1782 t18270531-332-viclabel1786"></join>, and live in West-street, Smithfield. I was in <placeName id="t18270531-332-crimeloc1787">Field-lane</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18270531-332-crimeloc1787" type="placeName" value="Field-lane"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18270531-332-crimeloc1787" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270531-332-off1784 t18270531-332-crimeloc1787"></join>, a quarter before seven o'clock in the evening of the 19th of May; I felt something all at once pulling at my pocket - I turned round and saw the prisoner with my handkerchief in his hand, and he shuffled it up his coat - I pushed him against a shop, and accused him of it; he said he knew nothing of it, but he dropped it in two or three minutes, and I collared him, and took him to the watch-house; he had not run; I saw the handkerchief in his hand, and saw him drop it.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. Was there not another gentleman with you? A. Yes, my brother - and there was a boy with the prisoner, and I saw the handkerchief shifting from that boy to the prisoner: my belief is, that the other picked my pocket and passed it to the prisoner - I seized the prisoner, and put him up against a shutter, that in case he dropped it, I might see it - I believe I did state at Guildhall, that the boy handed the handkerchief to him; the other was nearer to me; I know the boy's face; I have seen him there.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182705310126"></xptr>THOMAS WHITE. I am an officer. I received charge of the prisoner.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I was standing in the lane with my hands in my pockets, looking at some men mending the sewer. I saw the prosecutor and a gentleman pass me; the handkerchief was thrown, and rested on my elbow. I never moved, nor pulled my hands out of my pockets; there were a number of people who said I was not the man.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 28.</p>
               <p>
